RIFT VALLEY FEVER - EASTERN AFRICA (14): ANIMAL VACCINATION, FAO ALERT
**********************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

In this update:
[1] Kenya, Kajiado county, animal vaccination
[2] FAO - Eastern Africa, alert message

******
[1] Kenya, Kajiado county, animal vaccination
Date: Tue 10 Jul 2018
Source: Kenya News [edited]
http://www.kenyanews.go.ke/vaccination-to-curb-spread-of-rvf-in-kajiado/


Kajiado County government [Tue 10 Jul 2018] embarked on a massive vaccination exercise to curb spread of Rift Valley Fever [RVF] in the County.

County Director of Veterinary Services, Dr. Jackton Achola told KNA that the disease was quickly spreading in the County, hence endangering lives of thousands of livestock, as well as human beings who might end up consuming meat from affected animals.

"Following the heavy downpour that was experienced in the county during the March to May rainy season, there have been reported cases of mortality and abortions in Kajiado South, Kajiado Central and Kajiado West constituencies.

Samples tested positive for RVF in Entonet/Lenkisim ward, as well as sheep and goat plague - Peste dets Petits Ruminants PPR - a highly contagious disease affecting small ruminants tested positive in Ilodokilani ward, Kajiado West constituency," Achola said.

Already, the County government of Kajiado has acquired 60 000 doses of RVF vaccine from the Regional Pastoral Livelihood Resilience Project (RPLRP) and 200 000 doses of PPR (Peste dets Petits Ruminants) vaccine from Food and Agricultural Organization (FAO) for use in the County.

The County government has also issued a quarantine notice, covering, Entonet/Lenkisim and Matapato South wards in Kajiado West and Central Sub-counties, to restrict the movement of livestock and its product from the affected areas.

The veterinary department has enhanced livestock disease surveillance, both in affected and the neighboring areas, as well as conducting public health education with all field and abattoir staff, to be more vigilant and enhance surveillance in their areas of jurisdiction.

[Byline: Rop Janet/Albert Lemomo]

